The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services like their partners in Western Europe.
There is still something missing – a virtual operator who forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that the Czech operators belong to the most beloved in Europe has already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, ČTú also confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the final steps of the European Commission in the field of regularisation of roaming rates perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and highly over 100% coverage.
Instead, mobile telophony operators like to boast that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he often also emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) , Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network is no longer likely to have many possibilities. (The rest perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable lowering of prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices sounded in Britain like we did.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can really succeed.
At the end of the day, for example, we must not go too far.
In February this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete brewing group.
In order to be able to function effectively, many fewer customers than a traditional operator are sufficient.
They are not behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low price, which is often in balance with the supply of the most limited services
For example Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move even the bet on a bet-group not recently.
This operator aims to say specifically about men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and that they can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company who produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can also be affirmed by us in Poland.
He doubted the press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have much expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will happen rather in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta Financial Group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything because no potential competitors are created.
For some time now it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it gets better first.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have to have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, there is an impenetrable wall of silence around its creation.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeń of the press section of Telefònika O2.
Other operators are also involved in the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-Mobil's press spokesman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
He adds: "In the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered at the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on reaching its 3G licence applications.
He adds Miroslav Čepický: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most produced.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile telephone operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles surrounding the creation U:fon testify that when operators care about one thing they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against ČTú during the creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public information access from ČTÚ's websites.
But now U:fon itself serves as a topic for which the virtual operator does not accept.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The environment of competition in the mobile telephony market has been greatly enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put on him and above all on his high services."
However, the attitude of mobile telephone operators is quite surprising because of the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTú which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position with regard to the whole issue.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, from the UOHS External Relations Section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the operators' representatives may not be surprising.
Instead of the office that has to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "To abroad where virtual operators usually work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question as to whether this is really just a coincidence, is put on its own.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrols is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour about this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the day logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators do so strangely similar.
At the same time the complaints by the interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during the negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTú in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which UOHS is kept out of the whole thing.
This has already been found in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law has been updated, despite the fact that many experts expected the improvement of the situation from this point of view.
This is what UOHS representatives need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks
While the functioning of such pseudo-virtual operators, some of which exist in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile telephone services that are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the specified persons.
The magic lies in the fact that the company against the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile telephone operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If there were any cases that you are talking about, which we will be interested in, it could be a breach of contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned above, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot dispose in full of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a little strange at the ČTú.
In addition, there is another question for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a significant lowering of prices for services.
At the same time, virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators were trying more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries precisely in these cases the governing bodies have intervened in defence not of mobile telephone operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and he received others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory organs throw each other the whole case as a boiling potato.
For our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
But we don't throw away the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will really appear to us soon, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on the move.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly UOHS could remain impassable to the rejection (discrimination) of the other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
