Alcoholic reciprocating drivers will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative sanctions for excessive alcohol in their blood, to install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a state of drunkenness or if it does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney General's Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since he will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
In addition to the Attorney General's Office for Road Safety, this initiative will be attended by the Directorate General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Tecnologico per la Segurità dell'Automobile (FITSA).
According to the statistics, between 30% and 75% of the drivers reported more than once for drunk driving then return to driving the car.
The alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the breathed air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than that allowed.
The cost is greater than EUR 1000 and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow for a reduction of up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to stop these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And in order to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and without a doubt the necessary reform for criminal proceedings would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote for an initiative of the PSOE in which it intends to install this system on school buses, as has already been done in France.
