Talk in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who speak while remaining asleep.
The first time it happens, at most it takes a scare, but it doesn't really matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep defined as sleepiness.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you have spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (to pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overcrowded situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not yet been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (scream, scream, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a relief to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. when coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose peaceful games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is hard to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepyos appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
