The meeting - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, since Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, it regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of blood infected between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee to develop a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gelineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people declared that they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and to research on the field over the following years, we regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had already trusted in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, many cases of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were seen in Europe, and she is at the chair since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely didn't know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports that when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, take exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease is without a doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: the tests of nucleic acid (TAN) that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and of not being able to identify them is thus significantly diminished.
These improvements have led to a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years to find a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
As cancer cures are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors."
All healthy persons who have reached the age of 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Weak cases are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today life is so frantic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye-glob heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Québec that manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth blood cord sample and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of collecting cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it", as hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
