Operation - rescue for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the head of Congress, representatives of the Republican and democratic leadership, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the greatest saving-finance plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion US plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months, still needs to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
It provides in particular: checks on its actual implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses charged for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection on remuneration paid to managers of protected enterprises.
The American Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day talks marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been made in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted this way, invaluable discomfort and unrest would have turned on the daily lives of Americans," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new failure on investors.
The limited time allowed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
Together with the negotiations later on, the two candidates for the US presidential elections were quite in favour of the agreement, but they did not want to express their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama has the merit of adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow the owners to maintain their home and the one related to the remuneration for the managers of companies covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
