The psychology of excessive bidding: why spend more money?
At auctions buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study in Science magazine, men do not want to stay back in a race like eBay auction, so they are also available to pay a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "party" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body striated under the cerebral cortex enters intensely in function when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by scanning the vehemently reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the research group economists conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups appealed against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported how much the actual value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they have promised that in the event of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in case of auction losses.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to make higher bets of the control group or "win".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These, in fact, so far explained the phenomena found at the auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to contact your doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are cured: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver disease caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms according to the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g., water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal losses, saliva).
For those travelling, vaccination against A and B virus is useful, and against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellow spots are formed on the skin and white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide for hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subduly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory examination also reveals the disease, it is worth talking to your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated by the body, thus ceasing infectious power and preventing the formation of tumors.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a sort of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University carried out an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the quite bizarre investigation, an electroshock was made to 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all observed a painting depicting the virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University are also involved in addition to academics.
The test was carried out exactly this way: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the hermitage of Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the virgin Mary would give rise to a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's picture was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to have a peaceful effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time circle received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while watching or painting on religious or other themes.
Catholics reported that the vision of the virgin Mary made them feel "secure", as if "someone took care of" them and "were reassured and pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious picture, they accounted for 12% less pain than when Leonardo's work was before him.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with strong effect even for the atheists, but we must find the right image.
"We have to look for an image to which very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father, are nourished" said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the result of the search.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality." - Wright added.
After the excellent results only the question remains if the painting of a Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of such calibre is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
