The smart machine mimics the flight of the calabrone
What could be the best method for developing anti-collision technologies if not imitating the sensors of the obstacles in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented to CETEC in Japan, the calabrons gave the initial strategic start to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a mini robotized car with bees properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form one's own oval personal space that really resembles our protective shield - it explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the field technologies PR and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a visual of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have drawn to the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board that turns it immediately into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place entirely instinctively.
"If it weren't for the robot car, he wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot auto project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in a heartbeat.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go upwards or downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and with a high energy density, which means that their duration is longer than lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the promptness of the intelligent reaction, not data processing or even less the ability to store it, is important.
This robot needs to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a few tens of Kb memory.
There's no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, in anticipation of Nissan, can be installed on serial vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibility of application can be represented by unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leads to destination.
