Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organised by France this year with the rotating presidency of the European Union, began.
Livia Járóka, Fidesz Member of the European People's Party, in the message addressed to the plenum as the main rapporteur of the Congress, drew attention to school segregation because it is the most serious legal violation that affects Roma children and also the most serious obstacle to their affirmation.
Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and European Commissioner Vladimír Špidla, responsible for employment, social affairs and equal opportunities, opened the conference at the highest level.
The conference was attended by governments, European social partners and representatives of major European civil and rights organisations in the context of equal opportunities.
Járóka, according to the press office of the parliamentary group Fidesz PE, has pointed out, in addition to the discrimination in recruitments, that the Roma are being expelled from the labour market primarily because of their low schooling.
"Most Roma young people do not have an average degree of study and as a result of poor quality elementary education only a few of them are able to achieve a higher degree of study."
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in asserting human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member, it is necessary to make these links more aware in the wider context between Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner a Roma school begins, the more they increase their chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation's budget.
"The right of European citizenship of Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" – said Livia Járóka.
According to the honourable Member, the European Union's unity of purpose and action is necessary in order to speed up the process of disintegration of schools, and for this reason it is of fundamental importance that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives be complied with.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be stopped, Roma children must be given the opportunities given by the democratic space to contribute as citizens in full terms of the future of Europe" - Járóka asked.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised every year, since last year's Berlin meeting, is to ensure a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at state and European level.
