Listening to high volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a press release in Brussels cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is read in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than one hour a day holding the apparatus at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - the responsible EU continues - there is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and take the step with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard which limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but raises concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these damage by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours per week exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum noise allowed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
