The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion saving plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
It confirms yesterday's New York Times by informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old, moderate East Coast soul, in favour of federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "D Washington people" and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and South States.
The soul, for the point, which became prepotentially alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just mentioned, however, is only an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may preannounce or already let it see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to function as an accelerator of long-term incubation phenomena that solidify and finally come to light in the new climate.
The first of these phenomena is the realization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-subsidiarity in relation to a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, yes, have strong links with abroad, but which first and foremost see the budgets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State, to a great extent.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of play or not to have much to say: the flash test is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies cannot decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and re-launch plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the narrow it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in sixth place.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organization will likely ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from a point of view that our future will have to do more and more with those very immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at a bit, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who are sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which predicts a fracture.
Those who say Territory, State, Government, inevitably say Politics, and thus Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for self-reliant leadership, the demand of someone who can take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, revealed so inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And together something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: a disbelief, an indifference, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
In other words, there seems to be an increasing trend, in large sectors of the population, towards the belief that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly feeds a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political attitudes, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" of elections or in the sudden unfolding of collective moods of these very last and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Baviera to the collapse of the Labourist consents in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
You have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it more and more difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape today in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is invigorating, increasing, potentially agitating.
In the face of all this, speaking of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not for nothing.
