Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna has 82 single-sala cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to prove that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for practitioners: the State's previous debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
In order to support the sector, it would be between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, has decided to run to the shelter with the signing of a protocol between Town and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote monosala cinemas both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules provided for are tax facilitation measures for managers and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for the stopover and in some parking lots.
"It's an initiative I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is true, however, that in order to counteract the overpowering of multiplexes traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
