The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalists and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 per cent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea-moving facilities.
This amount would be twice as much as currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
