In order to produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such installations under design, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
The Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use energy.
